a viewable feast sulair sulair home searchworks e journals databases off campus access ask us special collections & university archives blog home staff bios search special collections & university archives blog library web sites searchworks databases az socrates google books google scholar search this site user login login with your sunet id home groups special collections & university archives blog a viewable feast fri 08 20 2010 14 22 a great find here in the department of special collections is the charles d field collection of ernest hemingway not only does this collection include articles and photographs about ernest hemingway it also has many of his first edition books along with many of his original correspondence i definitely suggest browsing through his correspondence in particular a letter hemingway wrote in 1951 to a princeton professor carlos baker in which he casually mentions how gertrude stein discovered the phrase the lost generation having become one of the most iconic phrases describing the 20th century it is interesting to see that this phrase did not originate from a great literary or political figure as most of us probably assumed but rather from a garage keeper in the midi france helping gertrude stein with her broken down car the garage keeper remarked that his young workers returning from the war were the lost generation as this letter infers when hemingway heard this phrase from gertrude stein it stayed with him throughout his life he used it as a quotation to open up one of his greatest books the sun also rises which was published in 1924 and as a source for a chapter of a moveable feast which he wrote in 1961 this letter is found in the charles d field collection of ernest hemingway m440 box 2 folder 2 and well worth seeing for yourself tnoakes stanford edu's blog login to post comments back stanford university stanford california 94305 650 725 1064 terms of use copyright complaints
